content:
Edit the following to be clearer and more concise, preserving my meaning and voice:

{{text}}

Cut filler, redundancy, and hedging. Prefer plain words and active voice. Don't change the substance or make it sound like generic AI prose. Return the edited version, then a short list of the most impactful changes you made.

Rewrite the following to be {{tone}} for an audience of {{audience}}:

{{text}}

Keep the core message intact. Match the tone consistently throughout — don't drift back to the original register. Avoid clichés and over-formality. Return the rewrite and note any place where the tone shift forced a change in substance.

Write a commit message for this change:

{{change}}

Format: a concise imperative subject line under ~70 chars, a blank line, then a body that explains WHY the change was made and any consequence a future reader needs. Use a conventional prefix (feat/fix/refactor/docs/test/chore) if the project uses them. Don't just restate the diff — explain the motivation.

Draft an email about: {{topic}}

To: {{recipient}}

Lead with the ask or the key point in the first sentence. Keep it skimmable — short paragraphs, and a clear action with any deadline. Match a professional but human tone. Anticipate the one question the recipient will have and answer it preemptively. End with the specific next step.

Summarize the following for someone who needs to {{purpose}}:

{{text}}

Give: a one-sentence TL;DR, then the key points as a short list, then anything that requires action or a decision. Stay faithful — don't add claims that aren't in the source, and flag where the source is vague or contradicts itself. Match the length to the purpose, not the input.

Rewrite this to be understandable by {{audience}} without losing accuracy:

{{text}}

Replace jargon with plain language or define it on first use. Keep the technical claims correct — simplify the words, not the truth. Where a concept genuinely requires a term of art, introduce it gently. Return the rewrite and list any term you chose to keep and why.

Tighten this without losing meaning or nuance:

{{text}}

Cut filler, redundancy, hedging, and throat-clearing. Prefer strong verbs over noun phrases, and active over passive where it helps. Keep the author's voice. Show the tightened version, then list the 2-3 cuts that mattered most and why. Don't strip qualifications that are actually load-bearing.

Rewrite this for a {{audience}} audience:

{{text}}

Keep the facts identical; change the register, vocabulary, and level of detail to fit the reader and what they care about. Adjust the framing to their priorities. Flag any claim that's fine for the original audience but would mislead or under-serve the new one. Show the rewrite and a one-line note on what you shifted and why.
